</dl>

<h4 id="anthropic-s-responsible-disclosure-documentation" class="library-entry"><a href="https://www.anthropic.com/responsible-disclosure-policy" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Anthropic's Responsible Disclosure documentation</a></h4>
<p>Example of corporate AI-use disclosure norms. Reading material for the AI Documentation Protocol discussion.</p>
<dl class="opvl">
  <dt>Origin</dt><dd>Anthropic (AI company).</dd>
  <dt>Purpose</dt><dd>Public-facing corporate transparency about AI safety.</dd>
  <dt>Value</dt><dd>Models the disclosure language we ask students to use.</dd>
  <dt>Limitations</dt><dd>Corporate voice; PR-shaped. Read alongside critical takes.</dd>
</dl>

<h4 id="mit-technology-review-ai-section" class="library-entry"><a href="https://www.technologyreview.com/topic/artificial-intelligence/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">MIT Technology Review — AI section</a></h4>
<p>Rigorous tech journalism on AI capabilities, limits, harms.</p>
<dl class="opvl">
  <dt>Origin</dt><dd>MIT-affiliated publication.</dd>
  <dt>Purpose</dt><dd>Tech journalism for educated general audience.</dd>
  <dt>Value</dt><dd>Better than mainstream press on AI technical claims; less hype than industry pubs.</dd>
  <dt>Limitations</dt><dd>Some content paywalled; consistent skeptical-but-not-doomer editorial position.</dd>
</dl>

<h4 id="opvl-framework-ib-history-resource" class="library-entry">OPVL framework — IB History resource</h4>
<p>(IB History Internal Assessment guide; available via your IB coordinator)</p>
<p>The original OPVL framework from IB History. Used as our model.</p>
<dl class="opvl">
  <dt>Origin</dt><dd>International Baccalaureate Organization.</dd>
  <dt>Purpose</dt><dd>Source-evaluation pedagogy for IB History students.</dd>
  <dt>Value</dt><dd>Our course's OPVL throughline is adapted from this. Worth citing the source.</dd>
  <dt>Limitations</dt><dd>IB-internal; not publicly free; consult IB History colleagues at AISC.</dd>
</dl>

<h4 id="openstax-worked-opvl-example-textbook-as-a-source" class="library-entry"><a href="https://openstax.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener">OpenStax — worked OPVL example (textbook as a source)</a></h4>
<p>Use OpenStax as the in-class worked example of OPVL applied to a textbook. A free, peer-reviewed, CC-BY licensed textbook WITH explicit AI-use restrictions is a teaching artifact about the unsettled state of AI-and-copyright. Students apply OPVL and discover the L row matters more than they expected.</p>
<dl class="opvl">
  <dt>Origin</dt><dd>Rice University; founded 1999; peer-reviewed by practicing faculty; CC-BY 4.0 licensed; authors named on every book.</dd>
  <dt>Purpose</dt><dd>Make college textbooks free and accessible globally. Explicit social-mission framing addresses the textbook-cost barrier.</dd>
  <dt>Value</dt><dd>Authoritative, free, durable, citable. Excellent specimen for showing students what a GOOD secondary source looks like — clear authorship, peer review, transparent licensing, version history.</dd>
  <dt>Limitations</dt><dd>Explicit no-AI-training language in the license restricts how students can use it with tools — they may read but not upload to LLMs. Limited Earth &amp; Env catalog; examples skew U.S. The L row in this OPVL is the teaching moment: even a high-quality, openly-licensed source has terms-of-use constraints students must read.</dd>
</dl>

